also why would my repo be building out over 16k test  files? all in one exe? is this smart it takes forever to compile....\par
\par
Short answer: no, that is not smart, and it usually means your build system is misconfigured.\par
If your repo is compiling 16,000+ test files into one executable, something is wrong with how CMake / premake / build scripts are collecting sources. This will absolutely destroy compile times and make iteration painful.\par
\par
Let\f1\rquote\f0 s break down why this happens and how to fix it.\par
\par
1. Why you are getting 16k files in one EXE\par
Most common cause:\par
\par
file(GLOB_RECURSE SRC *.cpp)\par
add_executable(Game $\{SRC\})\par
This grabs EVERYTHING:\par
\par
engine\par
\par
editor\par
\par
tools\par
\par
tests\par
\par
third-party\par
\par
examples\par
\par
old files\par
\par
temp files\par
\par
generated files\par
\par
So your EXE ends up compiling:\par
\par
/engine/*\par
/editor/*\par
/tests/*\par
/tools/*\par
/thirdparty/*\par
/old/*\par
/experimental/*\par
If you have GoogleTest / Catch2 / unit tests, this explodes fast.\par
\par
Result:\par
\par
huge link time\par
\par
huge compile time\par
\par
massive binary\par
\par
bad incremental builds\par
\par
2. Another common cause \f1\emdash  building tests into runtime\par
You might have something like:\par
\par
add_subdirectory(tests)\par
target_link_libraries(Game tests)\par
or worse\par
\par
add_executable(Game\par
    main.cpp\par
    tests/test1.cpp\par
    tests/test2.cpp\par
    tests/test3.cpp\par
)\par
Tests should NEVER be in the main game exe.\par
\par
Never.\par
\par
